Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel!). Pop the wedges on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @oil{}, then season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking. At the same time, pop another one (or two) large baking trays into the oven ready for the pizzas.

Drain and roughly tear the @mozzarella{1}. Chop the @baby plum tomatoes{125}(quartered) in half. In a small #bowl{}, mix the @tomato passata{1/2} with the @dried oregano{1} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

When the wedges have 15 mins left, pop the @plain naans{2} onto the preheated baking tray(s). Use a #spoon{} to spread the tomato passata evenly over each, leaving a small border clear of sauce. Scatter over the mozzarella and half the tomatoes. Bake the naan-gheritas (excuse the pun) on the top shelf of your oven (just move the wedges down) until golden and bubbly, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @cucumber{1/2} then quarter lengthways. Chop widthways into small pieces. Pop the cucumber in a large bowl with the remaining tomatoes and the @baby leaf mix{50}. Add a squeeze of @lemon{1/2}(juiced) and a drizzle of @oil{} then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat just before serving.

While you wait, have a clear down and get ready to serve.

Serve the wedges and naan-gheritas with a helping of salad alongside and enjoy!